Gerald, Doc....ah Damn, I just wrote an long and eloquent piece on racism and realism, and my modem disconnected just as I began to hit the submit button below.  Gone.  Well, more over Lien, that kind of coincidence has got to have some karma or cosmic value.  I won't try and recapture it, let be just say that your recent posts have caused me some serious re-think, and one of the issues I re-thank (thank?) was the business of my emotions with my ex-neighbor.<br><br>
It is the guy, not his race that still pisses me off.  I am, or was, quilty of using a very poor example, and of lazy thinking.  Lazy thinking ALSO is a part of racism, hence the easily viewed overlap that you both saw.  Also my use of disability exams (a small and lopsidded sample group) to make sweeping generalizations was dumb, and kindly allow me to withdraw that. Again, lazy thinking.<br><br>
Perhaps, for me, one of the best spin off's of this site is that it confronts the reader (me) with the need to re think old and stale thinking.  Sometimes that is a slap to the forehead and a loud DUH, othertimes, it is a long and silent pondering at the screen.<br><br>
Doc Del, Sorry to hear that you are dueling with so many &quot;racists&quot; at the same time.  Please do not think of me on that list.  <br><br>
Gerald, point made and well taken. I absolutely flamed, but the onld anger in me was at a human being, ex neighbor, and not his race. As I stated, it was lazy thinking and a flame, and I absolutely don't want to burn the pot or the contents.<br><br>
Lien, as I know you are out there, I am quite able to think, re think, and learn, and I invite you to do the same.  I think it's your turn to explain your attitude at me, which I still have not understood.<br><br>
